\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Math 320 Take Home Final
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You will have from the start of class until midnight on May 1st to work
 on and submit the take home final.
 Please clearly number the start of a problem for your scratch work and
 for your solution.
 You are welcome to use any class notes and previous homework assignments
 when working on this exam.
 If you use any other resources (which is discouraged, but still allowed),
 please cite your sources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Computation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of these questions will be worth 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 points.
 Show your work to receive full credit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{3}\times D_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathbb{Z},H=4\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Find all of the cosets in 
\begin_inset Formula $G\slash H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\left(\mathbb{R}^{+},*\right)$
\end_inset

 be the group of positive real numbers under multiplication.
 Show 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:G\rightarrow G$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)=\sqrt{x}$
\end_inset

 is an automorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{C}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Find 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(x\right),r\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $2x^{2}+ix+1-i=\left(x+1\right)q\left(x\right)+r\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{deg}\left(r\left(x\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
5.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}+4x+3,4x^{3}+2x^{2}+1\in\mathbb{Z}_{7}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(x^{3}+4x+3\right)\left(4x^{3}+2x^{2}+1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Proofs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Your lowest scoring response to the next 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 questions will be dropped.
 Each question is worth 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the set of even real-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\left\{ f:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}|f\left(-x\right)=f\left(x\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in E$
\end_inset

 and define addition 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f+g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f*g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E,+,*\right)$
\end_inset

 forms a ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
7.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
a) 
\series default
Consider the integral domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Show 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle x^{2}-n\right\rangle =\left\{ r\left(x\right)\left(x^{2}-n\right)|r\left(x\right)\in\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right],n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
b)
\series default
 Show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]\slash\left\langle x^{2}-n\right\rangle \approx\mathbb{Q}\left[\sqrt{p}\right]$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is not a perfect square.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 and the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x^{2}-n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 from problem 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{7\text{a)}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

, then for what values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 will 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x^{2}-n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 be 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
a)
\series default
 A prime ideal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
b)
\series default
 A maximal ideal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Note: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 may be a perfect square in this problem.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
9.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\left\{ z\in\mathbb{C}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} |\left|z\right|=1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
a)
\series default
 Show 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\left(\mathbb{C}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} ,*\right)$
\end_inset

 the group of non-zero complex numbers under multiplication (Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|ab\right|=\left|a\right|\left|b\right|$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
b)
\series default
 Show 
\begin_inset Formula $G\slash H\approx\left(\mathbb{R}^{+},*\right)$
\end_inset

, the group of positive real numbers under multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
10.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

 is said to be nilpotent if 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Show the set of all nilpotent elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 form a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
11.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is said to be idempotent if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}=a$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:R\rightarrow S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 is idempotent in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is idempotent in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Bonus Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you answer this question, you will get 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 bonus points.
 If you do not wish to answer this question, write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no response
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and you will still get full credit for this question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
12.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is your favorite topic we covered in this semester?
\end_layout

